<subSubSection id="97EA653FFFFE78066FE6FEC9FE73F84D" pageId="2" pageNumber="139" type="description">
<paragraph id="DF4F36B4FFFE78066FE6FEC9FCA1FDC2" blockId="2.[151,1437,150,2013]" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">
<emphasis id="ED84EAA6FFFE78066FE6FEC9FEF6FEBC" bold="true" box="[199,345,330,356]" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">Description.</emphasis>
Body length (from apex of labrum to apex of elytra in preserved position) about 
<quantity id="18089B51FFFE78066BD4FEC8FAE1FEBD" box="[1269,1358,331,357]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1" pageId="2" pageNumber="139" unit="mm" value="4.1">4.1 mm</quantity>
, maximum width (greatest width of combined elytra) 
<quantity id="18089B51FFFE78066D94FEECFCA0FE51" box="[693,783,367,393]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="2" pageNumber="139" unit="mm" value="1.1">1.1 mm</quantity>
; head length (from apex of labrum to neck) 
<quantity id="18089B51FFFE78066A23FEECFAF4FE51" box="[1282,1371,367,393]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="139" unit="mm" value="0.7">0.7 mm</quantity>
, head width (including eyes) 
<quantity id="18089B51FFFE78066EBBFE10FDADFE75" box="[410,514,403,429]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.6" pageId="2" pageNumber="139" unit="mm" value="0.86">0.86 mm</quantity>
; pronotal length (along median line) 
<quantity id="18089B51FFFE78066C80FE10FC56FE75" box="[929,1017,403,429]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="2" pageNumber="139" unit="mm" value="1.1">1.1 mm</quantity>
, pronotal maximum width (including denticles) 
<quantity id="18089B51FFFE78066E2AFE34FECBFE09" box="[267,356,439,465]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="139" unit="mm" value="0.9">0.9 mm</quantity>
; elytral length 
<quantity id="18089B51FFFE78066D2BFE34FDCCFE09" box="[522,611,439,465]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="2" pageNumber="139" unit="mm" value="2.3">2.3 mm</quantity>
. Habitus elongate, nearly parallel-sided, weakly convex dorsally and ventrally; glabrous (
<figureCitation id="47CB2A31FFFE78066E71FE58FE3EFE2D" box="[336,401,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-17@3.[151,1436,179,1863]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Austronausibius aenigmatista sp. nov., holotype, 6816 [MAIG]: A—habitus, dorsal view; B—habitus, ventral view; C—details of left posterior pronotal and anterior elytral sides, black arrow indicates humeral denticle. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm (A, B) or 0.5 mm (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488333" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488333/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Dorsum and appendages with fine, short, weakly curved, semi-erect pubescence (
<figureCitation id="47CB2A31FFFE78066A17FE58FA3FFE2D" box="[1334,1424,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetId="figure-21@4.[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Austronausibius aenigmatista sp. nov., holotype, 6816 [MAIG], habitus: A—right lateral view; B—left lateral view; C—fronto-lateral view. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488339/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). Body and appendages unicolored, rufous (as preserved).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF4F36B4FFFE78066FE6FDA0FB0BFC35" blockId="2.[151,1437,150,2013]" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">
Head slightly transverse (measured including eyes), slightly convex, with two symmetrical oval impressions above antennal insertions; finely punctate, punctures rounded, dense, each puncture about as large as an eye facet (
<figureCitation id="47CB2A31FFFE78066FBEFDE8FEAAFD5D" box="[159,261,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-17@3.[151,1436,179,1863]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Austronausibius aenigmatista sp. nov., holotype, 6816 [MAIG]: A—habitus, dorsal view; B—habitus, ventral view; C—details of left posterior pronotal and anterior elytral sides, black arrow indicates humeral denticle. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm (A, B) or 0.5 mm (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488333" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488333/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">Figs. 1A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="47CB2A31FFFE78066E32FDE8FE98FD5D" box="[275,311,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetId="figure-21@4.[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Austronausibius aenigmatista sp. nov., holotype, 6816 [MAIG], habitus: A—right lateral view; B—left lateral view; C—fronto-lateral view. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488339/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">2C</figureCitation>
). Genae not expanded or raised. Frontoclypeal suture absent. Compound eyes relatively small and prominent, hemispherical, with coarse facets; without interfacetal setation; eyes widely separated, with distance between eyes about 5× transverse diameter of one eye. Temple short, length about 0.25× eye length (
<figureCitation id="47CB2A31FFFE78066BDDFD30FACFFD15" box="[1276,1376,691,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-17@3.[151,1436,179,1863]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Austronausibius aenigmatista sp. nov., holotype, 6816 [MAIG]: A—habitus, dorsal view; B—habitus, ventral view; C—details of left posterior pronotal and anterior elytral sides, black arrow indicates humeral denticle. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm (A, B) or 0.5 mm (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488333" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488333/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">Figs. 1A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="47CB2A31FFFE78066A4AFD30FA20FD15" box="[1387,1423,691,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetId="figure-21@4.[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Austronausibius aenigmatista sp. nov., holotype, 6816 [MAIG], habitus: A—right lateral view; B—left lateral view; C—fronto-lateral view. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488339/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">2B</figureCitation>
). Antennal grooves beneath head absent. Maxillary palpi short; terminal palpomere elongate, spindle-shaped, truncate. Antenna short, extending to middle of pronotum, weakly flattened, gradually thickening toward apex; with 11 antennomeres, with rather distinct loose club composed of 3 antennomeres; sparsely covered with fine semi-erect setae; antennomere 1 subcylindrical, 1.5× as long as wide; antennomeres 2–5 equal in size, conical, slightly dilated apically, elongate, about 2.0× as long as wide, slightly shorter and narrower than antennomere 1; antennomeres 6–8 trapezoidal, nearly as long as wide; antennomeres 9–10 subequal in shape and size, transverse, about 1.6× as wide as long, with concave anterior margin, dilated apically; antennomere 11 rounded, as long as wide, without small process apically; relative length ratios of antennomeres 1–11 equal to 9-7-7-6-5-5-5-5-5-5-8.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF4F36B4FFFE78066FE6FC74FDC6FB79" blockId="2.[151,1437,150,2013]" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">
Pronotum slightly elongate, 1.2× as long as wide, subparallel-sided; pronotal punctation rounded, fine (each puncture slightly smaller than compound eye facet), dense (distance between punctures about 0.5–1.0× diameter of one puncture); disc evenly convex (
<figureCitation id="47CB2A31FFFE78066D05FBBCFDD3FB81" box="[548,636,1087,1113]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetId="figure-21@4.[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Austronausibius aenigmatista sp. nov., holotype, 6816 [MAIG], habitus: A—right lateral view; B—left lateral view; C—fronto-lateral view. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488339/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
). Anterior and posterior pronotal edges arcuate. Each pronotal side with six denticles (
<figureCitation id="47CB2A31FFFE78066E17FBE0FE33FBA5" box="[310,412,1123,1149]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-17@3.[151,1436,179,1863]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Austronausibius aenigmatista sp. nov., holotype, 6816 [MAIG]: A—habitus, dorsal view; B—habitus, ventral view; C—details of left posterior pronotal and anterior elytral sides, black arrow indicates humeral denticle. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm (A, B) or 0.5 mm (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488333" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488333/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">Figs. 1A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="47CB2A31FFFE78066E8BFBE0FE60FBA5" box="[426,463,1123,1149]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetId="figure-21@4.[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Austronausibius aenigmatista sp. nov., holotype, 6816 [MAIG], habitus: A—right lateral view; B—left lateral view; C—fronto-lateral view. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488339/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">2B</figureCitation>
): anterolateral denticle most prominent, denticle at posterior angle sharp, four lateral denticles equal in form, weak and obtuse.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF4F36B4FFFE78066FE6FB28FD23F9D1" blockId="2.[151,1437,150,2013]" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">
Scutellar shield distinct, transverse, semicircular. Elytra elongate, 2.1× as long as wide combined, subparallelsided, slightly wider than pronotum, punctate-striate, with narrowly explanate lateral margins. Elytral punctation arranged in nine strial rows of larger, round, setiferous punctures (
<figureCitation id="47CB2A31FFFE78066CAFFB70FB89FAD5" box="[910,1062,1267,1293]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetId="figure-21@4.[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Austronausibius aenigmatista sp. nov., holotype, 6816 [MAIG], habitus: A—right lateral view; B—left lateral view; C—fronto-lateral view. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488339/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">Figs. 2A, 2C</figureCitation>
); shortened scutellar row absent. Inner interstriae of elytra flat, covered with minute secondary punctation (
<figureCitation id="47CB2A31FFFE78066CFAFA94FB9BFAE9" box="[987,1076,1303,1329]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetId="figure-21@4.[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Austronausibius aenigmatista sp. nov., holotype, 6816 [MAIG], habitus: A—right lateral view; B—left lateral view; C—fronto-lateral view. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488339/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
); interstria between striae 8 and 9 raised, forming shallow declivity (
<figureCitation id="47CB2A31FFFE78066D14FAB8FD20FA8D" box="[565,655,1339,1365]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetId="figure-21@4.[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Austronausibius aenigmatista sp. nov., holotype, 6816 [MAIG], habitus: A—right lateral view; B—left lateral view; C—fronto-lateral view. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488339/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
). Humeral angles with distinct sharp denticle (
<figureCitation id="47CB2A31FFFE78066B82FAB8FB53FA8D" box="[1187,1276,1339,1365]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-17@3.[151,1436,179,1863]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Austronausibius aenigmatista sp. nov., holotype, 6816 [MAIG]: A—habitus, dorsal view; B—habitus, ventral view; C—details of left posterior pronotal and anterior elytral sides, black arrow indicates humeral denticle. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm (A, B) or 0.5 mm (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488333" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488333/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
). Elytral setation fine, short, weakly curved, not arranged in herringbone pattern. Epipleura well-developed, reaching abdominal ventrite 3, widest at humeri, with three rows of weakly pronounced, rounded tubercles basally. Relative length ratios of prothorax to mesoventrite to metaventrite to abdomen equal to 6:2:3:10.5. Ventral surface of thorax densely punctate; prosternal process elongate, dilated apically. Metanepisternum narrow, long, with one row of punctures, 0.5× as wide as epipleuron at broadest point.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF4F36B4FFFE78066FE6F990FE6CF965" blockId="2.[151,1437,150,2013]" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">
Legs short and robust (
<figureCitation id="47CB2A31FFFE78066EEDF990FD80F9F5" box="[460,559,1555,1581]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-17@3.[151,1436,179,1863]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Austronausibius aenigmatista sp. nov., holotype, 6816 [MAIG]: A—habitus, dorsal view; B—habitus, ventral view; C—details of left posterior pronotal and anterior elytral sides, black arrow indicates humeral denticle. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm (A, B) or 0.5 mm (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488333" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488333/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">Figs. 1B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="47CB2A31FFFE78066D1DF990FD2DF9F5" box="[572,642,1555,1581]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetId="figure-21@4.[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Austronausibius aenigmatista sp. nov., holotype, 6816 [MAIG], habitus: A—right lateral view; B—left lateral view; C—fronto-lateral view. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488339/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">2B–C</figureCitation>
). Procoxa nearly round, mesocoxa oval, metacoxa oval, not extending laterally to meet elytron. Trochanters apparently without spines. Femora widened medially, simple (without denticles or teeth), with deep, longitudinal groove for reception of tibia. Tibiae curved, dilated apically. Tarsomeres simple (not incrassate or lobed); tarsomere 5 longest, about as long as tarsomeres 1–3 combined. Pretarsal claws simple, equal in size, long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF4F36B4FFFE78066FE6F944FCF8F8F1" blockId="2.[151,1437,150,2013]" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">
Abdomen (
<figureCitation id="47CB2A31FFFE78066E67F944FE64F939" box="[326,459,1735,1761]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1889,1913]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetId="figure-21@4.[151,1436,181,1865]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Austronausibius aenigmatista sp. nov., holotype, 6816 [MAIG], habitus: A—right lateral view; B—left lateral view; C—fronto-lateral view. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488339/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">Figs. 2A–B</figureCitation>
) with five visible, similarly articulated and punctate ventrites; ventrite 1 with femoral line closed, moderately produced posteriorly in from of almost right triangle; ventrite 5 rounded apically. Relative lengths (medially) of ventrites 1–5 equal to 2.5:2.0:1.5:1.2:1.8.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF4F36B4FFFE78066FE6F8B0FE73F84D" blockId="2.[151,1437,150,2013]" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">
<emphasis id="ED84EAA6FFFE78066FE6F8B0FEA9F895" bold="true" box="[199,262,1843,1869]" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">Note.</emphasis>
The closeness of procoxal cavities (whether internally closed or narrowly open) and the form of intercoxal process of abdominal ventrite 
<quantity id="18089B51FFFE78066D27F8D4FD9DF8A9" box="[518,562,1879,1905]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="2" pageNumber="139" unit="in" value="1.0">1 in</quantity>
the studied specimen is unclear due to the position of the legs and the opaque amber layer in those regions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="97EA653FFFFE78066FE6F81CFC64F805" pageId="2" pageNumber="139" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="DF4F36B4FFFE78066FE6F81CFC64F805" blockId="2.[151,1437,150,2013]" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">
<emphasis id="ED84EAA6FFFE78066FE6F81CFEE1F861" bold="true" box="[199,334,1951,1977]" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet “ 
<taxonomicName id="18F04D37FFFE78066D6FF81CFD70F860" authorityName="Alekseev &amp; Bukejs" authorityYear="2022" box="[590,735,1951,1976]" class="Insecta" family="Silvanidae" genus="Austronausibius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aenigmatista">
<emphasis id="ED84EAA6FFFE78066D6FF81CFD70F860" box="[590,735,1951,1976]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="139">aenigmatista</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” is used as noun in apposition and is derived from the Latin substantive meaning “enigmatist, one that proposes or speaks in riddles”.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="8B8F663CFFFF78076FB6F8E2FE65F819" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6488333" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6488333" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6488333/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" startId="3.[151,250,1889,1913]" targetBox="[151,1436,190,1863]" targetPageId="3">
